metadata.name: Skravert #134
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: palimpsest #17
metadata.description:
This project channels my old "cursed collage" work with my intense enthusiasm to work ///as fast as I can/// with digital tools
I like to work with very old, cheap and popular consumer magazines. All the analogical graphic resources that I use are images, photos, papers that friends , lovers and  acquaintances gave me when they learned of my need to understand how popular culture can be a personal oracle

metadata.name: Hatching #39
metadata.description:
Hatching is one of the main techniques for pen and pencil drawings, etchings and copper engravings. Hatching is a combination of lines that thus depict different depths, effects and expressions. 

In pen and ink drawings, shading is indispensable. It is, in fact, the way to place the deep black ink on the mostly white paper. Hatching in architectural drawings indicates the various materials, for example in detail drawings. Look at old masters such as Duerer, Rembrandt and Da Vinci and you will see what depth they create with just carefully placed lines. 

In this generative abstract work I have not included any features, but some combinations do occur more frequently. Others are rarer. 

Chances:

Black pencil 50%
Red pen 10%
Blue pen 20%
Magenta 10%
Green pen 10%

Linen background 50%
Paper background 25%
Card board background 25%

Parallel hatching 50%
Cross hatching 50%

Rectangles 90%
Diamonds 10%

There is a small mathematical chance of a very special one, with his own drawing material.

metadata.name: Los Osos 2422 #1582
metadata.description:
# Los Osos 2422

I was working on the next EmProps release when accidentally I opened a link to a bear utopic civilization through their existing metaverse. Or should I say "metabears"?

Enter Los Osos 2422. 

Four hundred years into the future bears live in a peaceful civilization heavily inspired by the generative art movement of our times. They are organized in districts that are sustained by bamboo, salmon, berries, and art! Los Osos are black, grizzly, panda, and polar, yet there are no distinctions between species; it's not like they were humans. 

They have different occupations but frequently bears change jobs giving birth to the most eclectic looks.

I took my sketchbook out to capture what I could and started drawing but my presence pissed them off. Ninjas, luchadores, and even a cybearpunk forced me to escape.  Is that a live gummy bear or am I just hungry? The story will continue...

-- 

Los Osos 2422 is a PFP art piece composed of 320 hand-made drawings made as an homage to the nascent generative art current fueled by Tezos blockchain technology in 2022. It features hundreds of references to artists and pieces in several generative and non-generative fields.

The project combines the assets together using a custom open-source algorithm that allows them to stack with the positioning in front and behind the character to create possibilities like shirt collars or hats, dynamic tinting to have hoodies or glasses with different colors, exceptions to give them laser eyes or a green apple in front of the face, complex set-ups to have different versions for some of the outfits, and chance control to allow precise control over the features.

--

Press 'S' on the keyboard to save it as an 1800 x 1800 pixels PNG.

metadata.name: Boro #114
metadata.description:
Boro is inspired by the Japanese mending technique of the same name, which means something mended, in particular something mended with small pieces of fabric and patterned over stitching. The technique makes the fabric both stronger and more beautiful.

To render at different resolutions please use keyboard characters 1 to 5, which will render the artwork at a square of 1000 to 5000 respectively.

metadata.name: Euphonic #837
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moiré effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: decay #48
metadata.description:
An ideal is imagined, a perfect circle or square. This starting place experiences the whims and whimsey of chaos and entropy, and while the original intent is visible in the final piece, it is abstracted almost beyond recognition. 

Created in p5.js. 10% of all future royalties to the original minter.

metadata.name: Blueprints of balance #19
metadata.description:
Balance in art is one of the basic principles of design, along with contrast, movement, rhythm, emphasis, pattern, unity, and variety. Balance refers to how the elements of art (line, shape, color, value, space, form, texture) relate to each other within the composition in terms of their visual weight to create visual equilibrium. That is, one side does not seem heavier than another.

But there is no balance without Chaos. And that is why for one hour everyday each Blueprint of balance let it go and turns into its alternative wild version.

metadata.name: Unicorn #509
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

Twitter: @unicorn_nft_art
Web: https://unicorn-nft.web.app/

by @lucky26puch, @AgataBaranova17
Made in 2022

License: CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: La Veranada #100
metadata.description:
My mother lives in the countryside with her husband and her work is the breeding and grazing of goats, cows and horses. They live a cyclical life marked by two big stages during their livestock year: "La Veranada" and "La Invernada".
The "invernada" is the place where they live during what we could call the long winter, that is, from April to November. "La Invernada" is below, in the plains, in the pampas, in accessible places, where it is easy to supply the animals with fodder.
"La Veranada" is the place where they go during the long summer, from November to April, it is above, in the mountain ranges, on the heights, where the summer pastures abound, where they go for months to take care, alone, of the goats, cows and calves.
The transfer of the animals to the summer pasture is called "Arreo", my mother's husband guides the animals on his horse. The "Arreo" lasts about 5 days.
In both places they live in what they call "el puesto". "El puesto" is their home.
In "La veranada", "El puesto" is simple. A common living room, with a wood stove, a table, some chairs and shelves to store flour, *"mate" and salt. A small bedroom replenishes the strength worn out by the daily work. Water for drinking, cooking and washing is drawn from a nearby stream.
Work is abundant. As a common element, both in winter and summer, my mother's husband rides a horse daily and, accompanied by his dogs, goes to "watch" the cattle.
As a final point I wanted to thank you for taking your time and reading the story behind this project that I really enjoyed doing it, and on my tw profile you can read this story with real photos.

*Mate: is an Argentinean infusion, which is present all day long in the life of people who live in the countryside. It give you energy.

Press "S" in live mode to save image 2600 x 3000.
Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run.
Created by Fernando. NFT License 2.0.

metadata.name: Rococo #474
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 150 · 100 · 70 · 50 · 40 · 35 every 8 minutes. Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Nature’s wild flourish and untamed growth wondrously represent the exacting function of beauty — a function that is at once useful and infinitely creative. Perhaps nowhere is this delicate symbiosis better observed than in the flower, wherein a pure balance of physical fundamentals exists beneath ornate patterns and elaborate aesthetics.

Amongst the layers of undulating, vividly colored petals, attention-grabbing stigma and stamen, and lusciously decorative features, nature’s organic abundance and disorder disguises its masterful propensity for precision. Each of the flower’s components evolve through unpredictable interactions with an unwieldy natural environment, creating spectacular adaptations that emerge from the tension between what attracts.

Rococo painters appreciated the organic fluidity found in flowers and vegetal forms, using their joyful abundance to depict a break from the rigid and stoic period the artists hoped to leave behind. They sought to reframe perfection away from predictability and toward compositions as surprising as the natural world around them.

Thus, ‘Rococo’ is a generative distortion of an old tradition: a digital painting created entirely with code that interprets and processes the natural world’s dichotomies. This painting algorithm builds upon natural structures while melding and moving their colors beyond form, growing randomly organic iterations that are as perfect as they are imperfect.

Created by Ori Ben-Shabat & Ronen Tanchum @Phenomenalabs
Creative contributions from Tender @tender_art

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Technical Details:

- Mobile/GPU Intensive
- Press “s” to save a .png of the artwork in live view
- Press “p” to render a high res output + press “s” to save a printable .png

metadata.name: Quantum Folly #110
metadata.description:
This piece explores humanity's vanity and obsession with controlling natural forces. In the end we are beholden to the whims of the universe and its rules. What we think is artificial is but nature's inclination.

As an atom gazes at the world it can see the arrogant hand of mankind imposing its will. We are nature's inane creation built from imperceptible, discrete particles.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Due to the nature of the system it may take some time to complete. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Features include: palette, orientation, architecture, particle rules, boundary seepage and colour displacement.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-07-21 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #342
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: Kagome #6
metadata.description:
Hexagram composed of interlaced triangles such that each point where two lines cross has four neighboring points, forming the pattern of a trihexagonal tiling.



Made with P5js
Press the 'S' key to save PNG file.

metadata.name: Limina #76
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.

metadata.name: Loomnatic #126
metadata.description:
"Loomnatic" is a lunatic loom who loves to weave. It sometimes generates fabrics you can see in real life. However, most of the time, its outputs would look extraordinary.

How the loom "weaves" a fabric:
- Create a vector field for the warp threads with the improved Perlin noise developed by Ken Perlin.
- Derive a new vector field from the old one for the weft threads by rotating its angles.
- Calculate the curve vertices with an algorithm developed by Bruno Jobard and Wilfrid Lefer that creates evenly-spaced streamlines of arbitrary density.
- Interpolate each set of curve vertices to form a Catmull-Rom spline and then convert it to a thread polygon with varying thread weights.
- Calculate the intersection polygons of all pairs of interweaving threads with math and geometry.
- Use the intersection polygons to create the textile effect during the drawing stage.

Every token can output in 13 different aspect ratios:
1x1, 3x1, 1x3, 3x2, 2x3, 4x3, 3x4, 5x4, 4x5, 16x9, 9x16, 16x10, 10x16

And downloadable in 4 different resolutions:
1. 1000px
2. 2000px
3. 4000px
4. 8000px

Click on the image in live view to unlock all these possibilities.

Created with Vanilla JavaScript.
